{"cursor":"2882","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{ infobox nobility\n| name = Hildgard of Vinzgouw image = Hildegard 1499.jpg caption = Hildegard\n| from noble family = Udalriching dynasty father = Gerold of Vinzgouw mother =\n| Emma of Alamannia spouse = Charlemagne birth_date = 758 birth_place =\n| death_date = death_place = Diedenhofen\n}} 'Hildegard' (758 – 30 April 783) was the Germanic daughter of count\nGerold of Vinzgouw and Emma of Alamannia, daughter of Hnabi, Duke of Alamannia.\nShe was the second wife of Charlemagne, As described by historians such as\nPierre RichÃ© (The Carolingians, p.86.), Lewis Thorpe (Two Lives of Charlemagne,\np.216) and others. Other historians list Himiltrude, described by Einhard as a\nconcubine, as Charlemagne's first wife, and reorder his subsequent wives;\naccordingly Hildegard is sometimes numbered as his third wife. See Dieter\nHÃ¤gemann (Karl der GroÃe. Herrscher des Abendlands, Ullstein 2003, p. 82f.),\nCollins (Charlemagne, p. 40.). who married her about 771. They had the\nfollowing children:\n* Charles, (772 or 773â811), Count of Maine from 781, joint King of the Franks\n  with Charlemagne from 800\n* Adelaide (773 or 774)\n* Pippin (773 or 777â810), born Carloman and later renamed at baptism, king of\n  Italy from 781\n* Rotrude (or Hruodrud) (777â810)\n* Louis the Pious, king of Aquitaine from 781, emperor from 813 (sole Emperor\n  from 814) until 840\n* Lothair, twin brother of Louis, died young in 780\n* Bertha (779â823?)\n* Gisela (781â808?)\n* Hildegarde (782â783?)\n","linknr":134,"url":"Hildegard_of_Vinzgouw","recorded":1374541575,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hildegard_of_Vinzgouw&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hildegard_of_Vinzgouw&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en